Files:
- platform/plugin-sdk/src/fetch.ts (fix httpStatusToToolError)
- platform/plugin-sdk/src/fetch.test.ts (add tests for non-retryable 5xx)

Context:
In fetch.ts, the httpStatusToToolError function maps HTTP status codes to ToolError instances. The 5xx branch (lines 36-40) currently marks ALL status >= 500 errors as retryable:

```typescript
if (status >= 500) {
  const retryAfter = status === 503 ? response.headers.get('Retry-After') : null;
  const retryAfterMs = retryAfter !== null ? parseRetryAfterMs(retryAfter) : undefined;
  return new ToolError(message, 'http_error', { category: 'internal', retryable: true, retryAfterMs });
}
```

This is wrong for non-transient 5xx codes. 501 Not Implemented means the server will never support this operation. Retrying is pointless and wastes agent budget.

Changes:
Change the 5xx branch to only mark transient codes as retryable:

```typescript
if (status >= 500) {
  const TRANSIENT_5XX = new Set([500, 502, 503, 504]);
  const retryable = TRANSIENT_5XX.has(status);
  const retryAfter = status === 503 ? response.headers.get('Retry-After') : null;
  const retryAfterMs = retryAfter !== null ? parseRetryAfterMs(retryAfter) : undefined;
  return new ToolError(message, 'http_error', { category: 'internal', retryable, retryAfterMs });
}
```

The test server in fetch.test.ts already has endpoints for /error-500 and /error-503 (which have passing tests). Add test endpoints for /error-501 and /error-505, then add test cases asserting retryable=false.

The fetch.test.ts server is an http.createServer with a large chain of url.pathname checks (starting at line 34). Add the new endpoint handlers there (using res.writeHead(501)/res.writeHead(505)). Then add test cases similar to the existing 'throws non-retryable ToolError with no category on 409 status' pattern.

Constraints:
- Do NOT change retryAfterMs behavior for 503 — it still reads Retry-After header
- Do NOT change behavior for 500, 502, 503, 504 — these remain retryable=true
- The TRANSIENT_5XX set should be defined inline inside the if block (no module-level constant needed)

Files:
- platform/plugin-sdk/src/timing.ts (fix waitUntil)
- platform/plugin-sdk/src/timing.test.ts (add test for predicate error in timeout message)

Context:
In timing.ts, the waitUntil function's check() closure catches predicate errors silently:

```typescript
const check = async () => {
  if (isSettled()) return;
  try {
    const result = await predicate();
    if (result) {
      cleanup();
      resolve();
      return;
    }
  } catch {
    // Predicate threw — keep polling until timeout
  }
  if (!isSettled()) {
    poller = setTimeout(() => void check(), interval);
  }
};
```

And the timeout handler:
```typescript
const timer = setTimeout(() => {
  if (isSettled()) return;
  cleanup();
  reject(new Error(`waitUntil: timed out after ${timeout}ms waiting for predicate to return true`));
}, timeout);
```

Changes:
1. Declare a `let lastPredicateError: unknown;` variable in the waitUntil promise body (before check() is defined)
2. In the catch block inside check(), save the error: `catch (err) { lastPredicateError = err; }`
3. In the timeout handler, append the error context to the message:

```typescript
const timer = setTimeout(() => {
  if (isSettled()) return;
  cleanup();
  const errorContext =
    lastPredicateError instanceof Error ? `: predicate last threw — ${lastPredicateError.message}` : '';
  reject(new Error(`waitUntil: timed out after ${timeout}ms waiting for predicate to return true${errorContext}`));
}, timeout);
```

The `lastPredicateError` variable is captured by closure, so the timeout handler reads its final value when it fires — JS closures capture by reference.

In timing.test.ts, add to the 'waitUntil' describe block:
```typescript
test('timeout message includes last predicate error when predicate always throws', async () => {
  try {
    await waitUntil(() => { throw new Error('predicate always fails'); }, { interval: 20, timeout: 100 });
    expect.unreachable('should have thrown');
  } catch (error) {
    expect(error).toBeInstanceOf(Error);
    expect((error as Error).message).toContain('timed out after 100ms');
    expect((error as Error).message).toContain('predicate always fails');
  }
});
```

Also add a test verifying that when predicate never throws (just returns false), the error message does NOT contain extra context:
```typescript
test('timeout message has no error context when predicate never throws', async () => {
  try {
    await waitUntil(() => false, { interval: 10, timeout: 100 });
    expect.unreachable('should have thrown');
  } catch (error) {
    expect((error as Error).message).toBe('waitUntil: timed out after 100ms waiting for predicate to return true');
  }
});
```

Constraints:
- Do NOT change behavior when predicate succeeds — the lastPredicateError tracking is purely informational for the timeout case
- Do NOT change the existing 'rejects on timeout with descriptive error' test — its exact message check will need updating only if the message format changes when there is no error (it should not change)
- The fix must not log predicate errors on every poll — only include them in the final timeout message

Files:
- platform/plugin-sdk/src/storage.ts (fix setLocalStorage iframe fallback error handling)
- platform/plugin-sdk/src/storage.test.ts (add test for iframe fallback write failure)

Context:
In storage.ts, setLocalStorage uses withIframeFallback when window.localStorage is undefined:

```typescript
export const setLocalStorage = (key: string, value: string): void => {
  ...
  log.warn(`setLocalStorage: localStorage unavailable, using iframe fallback for key "${key}"`);
  withIframeFallback(s => {
    s.setItem(key, value);
    return true;
  });
};
```

withIframeFallback is:
```typescript
const withIframeFallback = <T>(fn: (storage: Storage) => T): T | null => {
  try {
    const iframe = document.createElement('iframe');
    iframe.style.display = 'none';
    document.body.appendChild(iframe);
    try {
      const iframeStorage = iframe.contentWindow?.localStorage;
      return iframeStorage ? fn(iframeStorage) : null;
    } finally {
      document.body.removeChild(iframe);
    }
  } catch {
    return null;
  }
};
```

If `s.setItem(key, value)` throws QuotaExceededError, it propagates out of fn(), through the inner try-finally (which removes the iframe), and is caught by the outer `catch { return null; }`. No warning is logged.

By contrast, the non-fallback path (lines 117-124) always calls `log.warn` when setItem throws.

Fix:
The simplest approach is to wrap s.setItem inside the lambda to catch and log errors:

```typescript
log.warn(`setLocalStorage: localStorage unavailable, using iframe fallback for key "${key}"`);
withIframeFallback(s => {
  try {
    s.setItem(key, value);
  } catch (error) {
    log.warn(`setLocalStorage: iframe fallback failed for key "${key}"`, error);
  }
  return true;
});
```

This is the minimal change: the error is caught BEFORE withIframeFallback sees it, so withIframeFallback still returns `true` (the iframe attempt ran but the write failed). The outer catch in withIframeFallback is not involved.

Constraints:
- Do NOT modify withIframeFallback itself — it is used by getLocalStorage, findLocalStorageEntry, and removeLocalStorage which do NOT need failure logging (reads/removes returning null is a valid no-op outcome)
- Do NOT change the 'using iframe fallback' warning that already fires before the withIframeFallback call — that remains
- The fix must only be in setLocalStorage's call site, NOT in withIframeFallback

In storage.test.ts, add to the 'setLocalStorage' describe block's 'iframe fallback' subdescribe:
```typescript
test('emits log.warn when iframe fallback setItem throws QuotaExceededError', () => {
  const entries: LogEntry[] = [];
  const restore = _setLogTransport(entry => entries.push(entry));
  Object.defineProperty(globalThis, 'localStorage', { value: undefined, configurable: true, writable: true });
  const mockIframe = {
    style: {} as CSSStyleDeclaration,
    contentWindow: {
      localStorage: {
        setItem: () => { throw new DOMException('Storage quota exceeded', 'QuotaExceededError'); },
      },
    },
  };
  const createElementSpy = vi.spyOn(document, 'createElement').mockImplementation(() => mockIframe as unknown as HTMLIFrameElement);
  const appendChildSpy = vi.spyOn(document.body, 'appendChild').mockImplementation(() => mockIframe as unknown as HTMLIFrameElement);
  const removeChildSpy = vi.spyOn(document.body, 'removeChild').mockImplementation(() => mockIframe as unknown as HTMLIFrameElement);
  try {
    setLocalStorage('quota-iframe-key', 'value');
    // Should have two warnings: 'using iframe fallback' + 'iframe fallback failed'
    expect(entries.some(e => e.level === 'warning' && e.message.includes('quota-iframe-key'))).toBe(true);
    expect(entries.some(e => e.level === 'warning' && e.message.includes('iframe fallback failed'))).toBe(true);
  } finally {
    restore();
    createElementSpy.mockRestore();
    appendChildSpy.mockRestore();
    removeChildSpy.mockRestore();
    Object.defineProperty(globalThis, 'localStorage', { value: win.localStorage as unknown as Storage, configurable: true, writable: true });
  }
});
```
